The most likely cause of this issue is that the programmer forgot to enclose the three lines of code within a set of braces (`{}`) after the `if` statement. As the textbook page explains, without braces, an `if` statement only controls the execution of the single statement immediately following it. The subsequent two lines of code are therefore executing unconditionally, outside the scope of the `if` statement.

To fix this, you would need to add braces around all three statements that are intended to be conditionally executed. For example:

**Incorrect (Current State):**
```cpp
if (condition)
    statement1;
    statement2; // Always runs
    statement3; // Always runs
```

**Corrected (With Braces):**
```cpp
if (condition) {
    statement1;
    statement2;
    statement3;
}
```
This ensures that `statement1`, `statement2`, and `statement3` are all treated as a single block of code and will only execute if `condition` is true.

